The Sherman‚ÄìMorrison formula is a great tool! For invertible \(\mathbf{A}\in\mathbb{R}^{p\times p}\) and \(\mathbf{v}\in\mathbb{R}^p\), we have
\[
(\mathbf{A}+\mathbf{v}\mathbf{v}^{\scriptscriptstyle\mathsf{T}})^{-1}
=
\mathbf{A}^{-1}
-
\frac{
\mathbf{A}^{-1}
\mathbf{v}\mathbf{v}^{\scriptscriptstyle\mathsf{T}}
\mathbf{A}^{-1}
}{
1
+
\mathbf{v}^{\scriptscriptstyle\mathsf{T}}
\mathbf{A}^{-1}
\mathbf{v}
}
.
\]

Recall the parametric family from the previous part, and consider the Bayesian model
\[
\begin{aligned}
\theta &\sim \text{Gamma}(a_0,\,b_0) \\
x_i\,|\, \theta &\overset{\text{iid}}{\sim }F(x;\,\theta).
\end{aligned}
\]

Derive the posterior distribution \(p(\theta\,|\,x_{1:n})\);
Show that the posterior mean \(E(\theta\,|\,x_{1:n})\) can be written as a convex combination of the prior mean and the MLE;
Derive the posterior predictive distribution \(p(x_{n+1}\,|\,x_{1:n})\).

Recall that if \(\mathbf{x}\) and \(\mathbf{y}\) are jointly distributed according to
\[
